<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910325-0029</DOCNO><DOCID>910325-0029.</DOCID><HL>   Brady Renews His Call   For Lower Interest Rates</HL><DATE>03/25/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2</SO><IN>CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)</IN><GV>TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady renewedhis call for lower interest rates.   &quot;I've said for nine months that there's ample room forlower interest rates. I still think that's the case,&quot; Mr.Brady said yesterday on ABC's &quot;This Week with DavidBrinkley.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   The Federal Reserve has brought down a key short-terminterest rate, the federal funds rate at which banks lend toeach other, by 2 1/4 points since last summer. Fed officialswill meet this week to set policy for the coming months amidmixed economic signals. Consumer confidence has rebounded,but it isn't clear that the recession will end soon.Meanwhile, the latest consumer price figures rekindledinflation fears among some investors and Fed policymakers.   Mr. Brady's advice, however, was unambiguous. &quot;We're underclose fiscal restraints,&quot; he said. &quot;It seems to me inflationis not the worry. The worry is growth.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>